## 🗄️ 2. Supabase `pgvector` Search Architecture
Rather than paying Microsoft $70+/month for an idle Azure AI Search instance, we store vector embeddings of workspace files inside your existing Supabase database.

### Database Schema (SQL Migration)
We will run a migration on your Supabase DB to create the search table and indices:
```sql
-- 1. Enable the vector extension
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector;

-- 2. Create the document chunks table
CREATE TABLE project_file_chunks (
  id uuid DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
  project_id uuid REFERENCES projects(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  file_path text NOT NULL,
  chunk_content text NOT NULL,
  embedding vector(1536), -- 1536 dimensions for text-embedding-3-small
  created_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT timezone('utc'::text, now()) NOT NULL
);

-- 3. Create a vector index for fast similarity matching
CREATE INDEX ON project_file_chunks USING hnsw (embedding vector_cosine_ops);
```

### Chunking & Vector Sync Pipeline
1. When a user updates a file in the CloudCode Editor, a debounced background worker in the Next.js API reads the file.
2. The file is split into code blocks (semantic lines, class/function definitions).
3. The server calls the Azure OpenAI Embedding API (`text-embedding-3-small`) to generate a 1536-dimension float array.
4. The database updates the vector records for that specific file path.

